esley, Drakelow, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Morton, Derbyshire, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, England","Drakelow, Derbyshire, England":"Drakelowe, Derbyshire, England","Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, Engeland, Verenigd Koninkrijk"},"en":{"Abt 1345–1380":"about 1345–1380","1345–1380":"1345–1380","1345–1405":"1345–1405","1367–1445":"1367–1445","1368–Female":"1368–Deceased","1373–1405":"1373–1405","1328–1395":"1328–1395","1325–1350":"1325–1350","1373":"1373","1395":"1395","1350":"1350","Abt 1345":"about 1345","Bef 1367":"before 1367","1380":"1380","1325":"1325","1368":"1368","1445":"1445","1345":"1345","1367":"1367","1364":"1364","about 1366":"about 1366","1328":"1328","1405":"1405","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Gresley, Drakelow, Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Morton, Derbyshire, England":"Morton, Derbyshire, England","Drakelow, Derbyshire, England":"Drakelowe, Derbyshire, England","Colton, Staffordshire, England":"Colton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"de","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Dilip, Anirban, Gopal, Alok, Anindya, Arunava, Asit, Asok, Dibyendu, Goutam, Indra, Indranil.","Indian: variant of   Dey  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Dey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Gresley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of Family Names in Britain and Ireland © University of the West of England 2016","meanings":["English:  see  Greasley  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Greasley","meanings":["1  English: locative name, usually from Greasley (Notts) but possibly also from Gresley (Derbys). Some of the following early bearers may alternatively belong under (2), particularly the Lancs examples.","2  Norman, English: nickname, either from Old French  <i>greslet</i> ‘marked as by hail’, i.e. pitted or pock-marked, or Old French  <i>greslet</i>,  <i>gresli</i>,  <i>grailet</i> ‘thin, slim’. In early forms, the nickname has sometimes been confused with the place-name in (1).  Compare  Le Gresley   in Jersey and  <b>Greslé</b>,  <b>Grêlé</b> in France."]}]},{"name":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas de Gresley was born about 1345, in Colton, Staffordshire, England, his father, John de Gresley, was 18 and his mother, Alice Swynnerton, was 21. He married Thomasine de Wasteneys in 1364, in Drakelow, Derbyshire, England, United Kingdom. They were the pare